<div class="blurb">
<div class="header"><h1>Overview (updated 20260406)</h1></div>
<div class="body">

<h2>What is MSG / DSG?</h2>
<p>Monosodium glutamate (MSG) was first prepared in <span class="highlight">1908</span> by Japanese biochemist Kikunae Ikeda, with commercial production beginning in <span class="highlight">1909</span> <sup><a href="#src-msg-history">1</a>, <a href="#src-msg-history-2">2</a>, <a href="#src-msg-history-3">3</a>, <a href="#src-msg-history-4">4</a>, <a href="#src-msg-history-5">5</a></sup>. It is the sodium salt of glutamic acid, an amino acid. <span class="highlight">Glutamate occurs naturally in many foods</span> (tomatoes, cheese, mushrooms), but <span class="highlight">MSG is manufactured free glutamic acid</span> that is <span class="highlight">added to food</span> <sup><a href="#src-natural-msg">6</a>, <a href="#src-natural-msg-2">7</a>, <a href="#src-natural-msg-3">8</a>, <a href="#src-natural-msg-4">9</a></sup>.</p>
<p><em>Note:</em> Strictly speaking, MSG is not the same as L-Glutamate (the naturally occurring amino acid). MSG is the <strong>sodium salt</strong> of L-glutamic acid (L-glutamate + sodium). Only the L-enantiomer produces the umami taste; the D-form has no flavor.</p>
<p>Disodium glutamate (DSG) and related nucleotide enhancers (Disodium Guanylate, E627) were developed in the <span class="highlight">1960s-1970s</span> for synergistic use with MSG <sup><a href="#src-dsg-history">10</a>, <a href="#src-dsg-history-2">11</a>, <a href="#src-dsg-history-3">12</a>, <a href="#src-dsg-history-4">13</a></sup>. Both MSG and DSG break down into glutamate (glutamic acid) in the body.</p>
<p>Chemical formula: C<sub>5</sub>H<sub>8</sub>NO<sub>4</sub>Na (MSG), C<sub>5</sub>H<sub>7</sub>NO<sub>4</sub>Na<sub>2</sub> (DSG)</p>

<h2>Health Concerns</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Excitotoxicity</strong> (glutamate storms) - overstimulation of neurons <sup><a href="#src-excitotoxicity">14</a>, <a href="#src-excitotoxicity-2">15</a>, <a href="#src-excitotoxicity-3">16</a>, <a href="#src-excitotoxicity-4">17</a>, <a href="#src-excitotoxicity-5">18</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>Headaches / Migraines</strong> - documented trigger in multiple studies <sup><a href="#src-headache">19</a>, <a href="#src-headache-2">20</a>, <a href="#src-headache-3">21</a>, <a href="#src-headache-4">22</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>Digestive issues</strong> - constipation, gut microbiota changes, visceral pain <sup><a href="#src-gut">23</a>, <a href="#src-gut-2">24</a>, <a href="#src-gut-3">25</a>, <a href="#src-gut-4">26</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>Respiratory issues</strong> - asthma, sinus problems <sup><a href="#src-respiratory">27</a>, <a href="#src-respiratory-2">28</a>, <a href="#src-respiratory-3">29</a>, <a href="#src-respiratory-4">30</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>Skin reactions / Acne flare-ups</strong> - MSG may worsen existing skin conditions via gut-immune-skin axis <sup><a href="#src-skin">31</a>, <a href="#src-skin-2">32</a>, <a href="#src-skin-3">33</a>, <a href="#src-skin-4">34</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>True MSG allergy</strong> - Rare but documented Type I food allergy to MSG confirmed via oral challenge <sup><a href="#src-allergy">35</a>, <a href="#src-allergy-2">36</a>, <a href="#src-allergy-3">37</a>, <a href="#src-allergy-4">38</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>Skin/mucosal irritation</strong> - MSG on cracked skin or chapped lips may cause stinging (like salt on a wound) <sup><a href="#src-skin">31</a>, <a href="#src-skin-2">32</a>, <a href="#src-skin-5">39</a>, <a href="#src-skin-6">40</a></sup></li>
<li>Linked to: diabetes, multiple sclerosis, rheumatoid arthritis <sup><a href="#src-linked">41</a>, <a href="#src-linked-2">42</a>, <a href="#src-linked-3">43</a>, <a href="#src-linked-4">44</a></sup></li>
<li><span class="highlight">May suppress immune system</span> <sup><a href="#src-immune">45</a>, <a href="#src-immune-2">46</a>, <a href="#src-immune-3">47</a>, <a href="#src-immune-4">48</a></sup></li>
<li>Effects are <strong>cumulative</strong> with repeated exposure <sup><a href="#src-cumulative">49</a>, <a href="#src-cumulative-2">50</a>, <a href="#src-cumulative-3">51</a>, <a href="#src-cumulative-4">52</a></sup></li>
</ul>

<h2>PANS/PANDAS and MSG</h2>
<p><strong>PANS</strong> (Pediatric Acute-onset Neuropsychiatric Syndrome) is a neurological disorder affecting children, characterized by the sudden onset of OCD and/or eating restrictions along with symptoms in at least 2 of 7 categories including anxiety, mood/behavioral changes, cognitive issues, and sensory abnormalities.</p>
<p>A published case study documented a 50-year-old man with treatment-resistant OCD who experienced <span class="highlight">complete remission of OCD symptoms after 1 month on a low-glutamate diet</span>. When challenged with MSG in a double-blind placebo-controlled trial, his OCD symptoms returned &mdash; while placebo challenge showed no return of symptoms <sup><a href="#src-pans">53</a>, <a href="#src-pans-2">54</a>, <a href="#src-pans-3">55</a>, <a href="#src-pans-4">56</a></sup>.</p>
<p>This suggests <span class="highlight">a potential link between dietary free glutamate (MSG) and neuropsychiatric symptoms</span> in susceptible individuals. Given that PANS/PANDAS involves OCD as a core symptom, and that excitotoxicity (overstimulation of neurons by glutamate) is a documented mechanism, further research is warranted.</p>

<h2>The Problem</h2>
<ul>
<li>MSG is widely used in processed foods and quick-service restaurants (QSRs)</li>
<li>Restaurants are <strong>not required</strong> to disclose MSG use (trade secret)</li>
<li>Labeling laws don't require quantity disclosure</li>
<li>"No MSG" is impossible &mdash; only "no added MSG" is accurate</li>
<li><strong>Hidden sodium</strong> - MSG and DSG add sodium to diet without disclosure; DSG has 2x the sodium of MSG</li>
<li><strong>MSG + DSG together</strong> - Often used in combination for synergistic effect, amplifying both sodium and glutamate exposure <sup><a href="#src-synergy">57</a>, <a href="#src-synergy-2">58</a>, <a href="#src-synergy-3">59</a>, <a href="#src-synergy-4">60</a></sup></li>
<li>People on low-sodium diets may unknowingly exceed their daily limit</li>
<li><strong>MSG Symptom Complex</strong> (formerly "Chinese Restaurant Syndrome") - controversial but documented reactions in sensitive individuals <sup><a href="#src-symptoms">61</a>, <a href="#src-symptoms-2">62</a>, <a href="#src-symptoms-3">63</a>, <a href="#src-symptoms-4">64</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>Big snack brands admit it</strong> - Frito-Lay: "In order to maintain the taste that consumers have grown to love... we use extremely low levels of MSG in some products to enhance flavor" <sup><a href="#src-frito">65</a>, <a href="#src-frito-2">66</a>, <a href="#src-frito-3">67</a>, <a href="#src-frito-4">68</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>Skin contact</strong> - Avoid food with MSG on cracked/chapped lips; may sting like salt on a wound <sup><a href="#src-skin">31</a>, <a href="#src-skin-2">32</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>Military normalization</strong> - U.S. military has used MSG in rations since the Korean War (1950s). Modern MREs use <strong>Disodium Guanylate (DSG)</strong> in synergy with hidden glutamate sources (autolyzed yeast, hydrolyzed protein) to achieve the same umami effect <sup><a href="#src-military">69</a>, <a href="#src-military-2">70</a>, <a href="#src-military-3">71</a>, <a href="#src-military-4">72</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>Treating symptoms, not cause</strong> - People use water pills, pain relievers, antacids, etc. to treat MSG effects rather than avoiding MSG. This adds another layer of pharmaceutical burden to the body.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Key Facts</h2>
<ul>
<li>FDA considers MSG and DSG <strong>GRAS</strong> (Generally Recognized As Safe) <sup><a href="#src-fda">73</a>, <a href="#src-fda-2">74</a>, <a href="#src-fda-3">75</a>, <a href="#src-fda-4">76</a></sup></li>
<li>FDA threshold for symptoms: <strong>3 grams</strong> of MSG without food <sup><a href="#src-fda">73</a></sup></li>
<li>Typical serving contains less than <strong>0.5 grams</strong> of added MSG <sup><a href="#src-fda">73</a></sup></li>
<li>Average intake of added MSG: ~<strong>0.55 grams/day</strong> <sup><a href="#src-fda">73</a></sup></li>
<li>Average total glutamate (from protein in food): ~<strong>13 grams/day</strong> <sup><a href="#src-fda">73</a></sup></li>
<li>Hidden names include: yeast extract, hydrolyzed protein, autolyzed plant protein, disodium guanylate</li>
</ul>

<h2>Solutions: Detecting MSG/DSG</h2>
<p>Currently, there is no consumer-friendly test kit to detect MSG/DSG in food. Laboratory methods include:</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Mass Spectrometry (LC-MS/MS)</strong> - Gold standard for accurate quantification <sup><a href="#src-detect">77</a>, <a href="#src-detect-2">78</a>, <a href="#src-detect-3">79</a>, <a href="#src-detect-4">80</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>HPLC</strong> - High-precision measurement used in food testing labs <sup><a href="#src-detect">77</a>, <a href="#src-detect-2">78</a></sup></li>
<li><strong>Enzymatic Assay Kits</strong> - Moderate cost, requires spectrophotometer</li>
<li><strong>Test Strips</strong> - Detect L-Glutamate (MSG) via enzymatic reaction; semi-quantitative (0-300 mg/L), useful for screening but not precise <sup><a href="#src-teststrips">81</a>, <a href="#src-teststrips-2">82</a>, <a href="#src-teststrips-3">83</a>, <a href="#src-teststrips-4">84</a></sup></li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Project Goal:</strong> Develop a simple, affordable consumer test kit for detecting MSG/DSG quantity in food samples.</p>

<h3>Practical Tips</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Read the label</strong> - Always check ingredient lists for MSG (monosodium glutamate, E621), DSG (disodium glutamate, E622), and hidden names (yeast extract, hydrolyzed protein, etc.)</li>
<li><strong>Ask the restaurant</strong> - Politely ask if they use MSG in their food. Note: they may not know or may refuse to answer.</li>
<li><strong>Avoid breaded foods</strong> - At fast-food restaurants, avoid anything with breading (fried chicken, fish sandwiches) as these often contain MSG</li>
<li><strong>Avoid "fire hot" or "extreme flavor"</strong> - Products claiming extra spicy or intense flavor often use MSG to enhance taste</li>
<li><strong>MSG = profit move</strong> - MSG allows use of heavily processed ingredients while maintaining flavor. It's used to mask lower-quality inputs.</li>
<li><strong>Umami without MSG</strong> - Real chefs get umami naturally from aged cheeses, mushrooms, soy sauce, tomatoes, anchovies. No need to stoop to MSG.</li>
<li><strong>Umami comes from glutamate</strong> - The "savory" flavor comes from glutamate, not from salt. MSG = salt + glutamate <sup><a href="#src-umami">85</a>, <a href="#src-umami-2">86</a>, <a href="#src-umami-3">87</a>, <a href="#src-umami-4">88</a></sup>.</li>
<li><strong>Check for "natural flavor"</strong> - Ingredients labeled "natural flavor" may contain MSG or hidden glutamate <sup><a href="#src-natural">89</a>, <a href="#src-natural-2">90</a>, <a href="#src-natural-3">91</a>, <a href="#src-natural-4">92</a></sup>.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Mission</h2>
<p>To study the effects of consuming monosodium glutamate (MSG), especially over the long term, and to advocate for better labeling and disclosure in restaurants and processed foods.</p>

